[ECO "B50"]
[Annotator "GM Arturs Neiksans"]
[PlyCount "35"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {So, the dreaded Sicilian Najdorf! The variation which has
caused headaches for thousands of chess players due to the vast amounts of
theory to be studied. I think it's important to stop here a moment and try to
explain where the modern chess (not related to us, but in general) is heading.
For a long time, it was believed that studying theory for hundreds of hours
could bring you easy points without even working on the board. An excellent
example in this matter is one of the best chess players of all time Garry
Kasparov, whose supreme knowledge in theory often led people to say that he's
not even playing, but just demonstrating his expertise in the openings. Things
have changed, however. Due to the rapid evolvement of computer engines, and
overall rise of the defensive skills at the top level, not to mention the
ever-increasing competition, now more than ever it is believed that normally
Chess is a drawn game. If your opponent knows the theory at an acceptable
level and makes no apparent mistakes, it is tough to beat him. That's why many
off-beat variations to surprise the opponents started to become very popular,
and at the same time, it involved less studying of the actual theory. In
regards to achieving an advantage in the opening also the way of thinking has
changed. If previously the most common belief was that with White, you can
achieve an advantage with the perfect play, today more and more players strive
for positions that are pleasant, easy to memorize and play. So that's why many
side variations are being explored more often with the reasoning - if I can't
get an advantage in the main line, why not play some off-beat lines? The same
principle also applies here - there's nothing wrong with the main lines of
Najdorf, but if Black's doing fine there, perhaps you should try something
else which involves less study?} 3. Bb5+ {A very logical continuation as White
develops a piece with a check, which according to Chessbase database was first
played in 1939 World Women Chess Championship by a chess player from Belgium
Marianne Stoffels. Back then it was not a very popular choice and was
performed very rarely - 3.d4 was far more popular. The first contributors to
the rare line were Esteban Canal, Alexey Sokolsky, and Nicolas Rossolimo and
that's why the variation has been called in many names - Canal-Sokolsky attack
or Rossolimo variation. For the sake to not confuse you, I suggest that we
will stick to the Moscow variation title as I'll use the Rossolimo variation
title in the 2nd part of the Anti-Sicilian database 2... Nc6 3.Bb5. I'm not
sure from where the name comes from, but I can assume that it was given
because several Soviet grandmasters started to play it in early 1940-is at
some Soviet top-level tournaments, presumably in Moscow. Nowadays the Moscow
variation is extremely popular, and one of the reasons is the current World
Champion Magnus Carlsen. His approach to the chess has changed the way of
thinking for many - not to strive for advantage in the opening, but get an
easy play with a logical development of the pieces. Don't be mistaken though -
Magnus Carlsen may play off-beat variations, but he does know them well. Right
now pretty much all of the top level players who choose 1. e4 play a decent
amount of the Moscow variation as well. Now Black has three possible ways to
play. I've always believed that the main choice is between 3. .Bd7 or Nd7
although also 3...Nc6 is very much playable. At a competitive level 3...Bd7
means that Black doesn't mind to draw as many lines are peaceful but 3...Nd7
is more aggressive and more to the spirit of a true Najdorf player and leads
to an imbalanced play (if White agrees to that!). 3....Nc6 is less played and
also can be achieved from the Rossolimo variation 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 d6.}
Nc6 {The whole point of Black's plan is to play Bd7 next move, then drive out
the white bishop from b5 by playing a7-a6, and harmonically develop the pieces.
As soon as the bishop from b5 is gone, Black is ready to "waste" one more
tempo and reposition the bishop from d7 to g4, slowing down White's intentions
to grab the center.} (3... Bd7 {will be covered in Chapter 4-6}) (3... Nd7 {
will be covered in Chapter 7-9}) 4. O-O {If Black doesn't challenge White, he
will just play c2-c3 and d2-d4, taking the center. Now the only reasonable
alternative for White rather than the main line is to play} (4. Bxc6+ bxc6 5.
O-O e5 (5... Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. e5 $5 {Which automatically shatters Black's pawn
structure and makes the doubled c pawns as a target, but also gives up the
bishop pair and the center} e6 (7... dxe5 8. g4 e4 9. gxh5 exf3 10. Nc3 {
[%cal Gd1f3,Gd2d3,Gh5h6]}) 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. d3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4,Ge4g3,Gb1d2,
Gd2e4]} Ne7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Ne4 Nd5 12. Re1 Re8 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Ne4 Bc7 15.
Nxc5 e5 16. a3 f5 17. c4 Nf6 18. d4 e4 19. Ne5 Bh5 20. Qd2 Qd6 21. Qc3 {
1-0 (51) Shirov,A (2697)-Gelfand,B (2710) Dortmund 2002}) 6. c3 {with a
following breakthrough d2-d4 in the center}) 4... Bd7 (4... Bg4 $6 {This move
doesn't stop White from grabbing the center so can hardly be recommended for
Black} 5. c3 Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 (6... Nxe4 $4 7. d5 a6 8. Bd3 $18) 7. cxd4 a6 8.
Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nc3 e6 10. Qa4 Qd7 11. Nd2 d5 12. e5 Ng8 13. Nb3) (4... a6 $6 {
Now comparing to the alternative I was suggesting 4. Bxc6, in this line White
gains a whole tempo because of the useless a6 move for Black with the same
idea and that, should make a difference} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1 {
and Black loses the battle for the center. White can either go for d2-d4 and
harmonical development of the pieces or maybe even try e4-e5 and play for the
weak doubled c pawns}) (4... e5 $6 {also doesn't stop White from advancing
d2-d4} 5. c3 Nf6 6. d4 {and again} Nxe4 $4 {is impossible because of} 7. d5 a6
8. Bd3) (4... Nf6 $6 {allows White to start immediate action in the center} 5.
e5 $1 dxe5 (5... Nd7 6. exd6 e5 $6 {is a nice attempt for Black to grab the
center, but it just doesn't work!} (6... e6 7. d4 Bxd6 8. d5 exd5 9. Qxd5 $16)
(6... exd6 7. Re1+ Be7 8. Qe2 $16) 7. d4 $1 cxd4 (7... Nxd4 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. f4
Bxd6 10. fxe5 Bxe5 11. Qh5 Qe7 12. Bg5 {with a hazardous attack for White}) 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 10. Nb5 $1 cxb5 11. Qd5 Bxd6 12. Qxa8 $16) 6. Nxe5 Qc7 7.
Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Re1 e6 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gd1f3,
Gf3g3] with very comfortable initiative for White} Nd5 12. Nd2 f6 13. Nec4 e5
14. Ne4 Be6 15. Ba3 Nb4 16. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) (4... Qc7 $6 {This is an
interesting attempt to saves some tempos and take on c6 with a queen, but it
makes no difference as White's plan remains the same} 5. c3 a6 6. Bxc6+ Qxc6 7.
Re1 Nf6 (7... c4 {Black is attempting to stop d2-d4 from happening but at a
big cost - loss of time} 8. b3 b5 (8... e5 9. bxc4 Qxc4 10. d4 Qc7 11. c4 $1
Nf6 12. Bb2 $16) 9. a4 $1 {Since Black is seriously lagging behind in
development, it makes perfect sense to open up the position!} cxb3 10. Qxb3
bxa4 11. Rxa4 Nf6 12. Ba3 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gd2d4]}) 8. d4 Bg4 9. d5 Qc7 10. h3
Bh5 11. Bf4 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 5. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gc2c3,Gd2d4,Gb5f1] This move
is important because of two things - 1) it aims for a quick e4-e5 push if
needed, 2) in case defends the pawn on e4 if attacked by Nf6 and most
importantly, 3) frees the f1 spot for the bishop on b5 and prepare the
eventual c2-c3 and d2-d4} Nf6 (5... a6 {this is an interesting order of the
moves, but it changes nothing in White's concept. On the contrary - gives one
more option!} 6. Bf1 (6. Bxc6 $5 {now because there is no knight on f6, White
can aim for a quick d2-d4 and try to use his superiority in development by
opening up the position} Bxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Rc8 (8... Nf6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10.
Qf3 {[%cal Ge4e5]} e5 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nc4 O-O 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Rad1 $14) (8...
Bd7 9. c4 Nf6 10. Nc3 Rc8 11. b3 b5 12. Bg5 {1-0 (40) Anand,V (2793)-Nakamura,
H (2775) London 2014}) 9. Nxc6 Rxc6 10. b3 Nf6 11. Bb2 e6 12. c4 Be7 13. Nd2
O-O 14. Nf3 {with some pleasant pressure although nothing real}) 6... Bg4 7. c3
g6 {the interesting idea behind this move is to play not only the obvious Bg7,
but also Bh6, trading the bishops! However, there is no line where Black fully
equalizes} (7... e5 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 $1 Bg6 10. d4 Nf6 11. d5 Nb8 12. Nbd2 {
and Black is cramped, while White can play on both sides. In the queenside
a2-a4 with Nc4 makes a good plan while on the kingside Black can hardly
breathe.}) (7... Ne5 $6 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 Bd7 11. Nc3 $16) (
7... e6 {this is an interesting alternative for Black to postpone the
development of the g8 knight and see what happens first by playing e7-e6 and
d6-d5. Since White still is ahead in development, it only makes sense to open
up the position} 8. d4 d5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Be2 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf6 12. Nc3 Qa5
13. h3 Bh5 14. Be3 Be7 15. a3 O-O 16. Qb3 {White's position looks slightly
more promising, true to a typical Alapin variation position. One idea might be
to aim for d4-d5 and use the better development of White's pieces to claim an
advantage, another is going for g2-g4 and Nf3-e5, followed by Be2-f3}) (7...
Nf6 8. d4 {transposes to the main line}) 8. d4 (8. h3 $6 {now this is not
entirely accurate and perhaps what Black is hoping for as he gets an equal
game after a thematic dark-squared bishop eventual exchange} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Bh6)
8... cxd4 (8... Bg7 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. Be3 {is unpleasant for
Black!}) (8... Nf6 9. Be3 Bg7 (9... Nxe4 $4 10. d5 {[%cal Gd1a4]}) (9... cxd4
10. cxd4 Bg7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. Rc1 $14) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 cxd4 12. cxd4 O-O
13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Nb3 $14 e5 $6 15. Qd1 exd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Qxd4
Ne5 19. Rad1 Qg5 20. Re3 $16) 9. cxd4 e5 $5 (9... Bg7 10. d5 Ne5 {or 10...Nd4,
the idea remains the same. White shouldn't be worried about doubling the pawns,
if Black goes for it at all costs as it strengthens the center.} 11. Nbd2 Nf6
12. h3 Nxf3+ 13. Nxf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 O-O 15. Qb3 $14) 10. d5 Nd4 11. Be3 Bxf3
12. gxf3 Bg7 13. Nd2 Nf6 14. Nb3 {and Black probably has to sacrifice the pawn
on d4 by gaining some control on the dark squares, although probably not
enough to equalize the game} (14. f4 $5) 14... Nh5 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Bxd4 Qg5+
17. Kh1 O-O 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd4+ Qf6 20. Qxf6+ Kxf6 21. Rac1 Rac8 22. Bh3
Rxc1 23. Rxc1 a5 24. Rc7 Nf4 25. Bd7 b6 26. Rb7 $14) 6. c3 (6. h3 {This is an
alternative that can also be tried out, but I see nothing wrong with the main
line} a6 7. Bf1 e6 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 Nxd2
13. Bxd2 Qb6 14. Bc3 O-O 15. Bd3 f6 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Re3 Rf7 18. Qe2 Nd8 19.
Nh2 Bb5 20. Rg3+ Rg7 21. Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Qh5 Bxd3 24. Qe8+ Kg7 25.
Qxe7+ Nf7 26. Ng4 Qd8 27. Qxe6 {1-0 (35) Motylev,A (2685)-Pogromsky,M (2418)
Loo 2014}) 6... a6 {now if not only the pawn on e4 were double attacked, White
would probably prefer to take on c6 and push d2-d4. Since this is impossible,
the bishop retreats to f1. Retreating to a4 is an alternative.} 7. Bf1 Bg4 (
7... e5 {This early push in an attempt to fix the center might be premature as
it presents White a yet another option. He can push 8.d4 which can transform
to one of the promising main lines with a different order of moves, or maybe
even try 8.h3 and still get a very pleasant position. The thing about playing
8.d4 is that if Black doesn't want to go to the main lines with the eventual
Bg4 and Nd4, White has just saved a whole tempo for h3! However, it closed
positions extra tempos might not feel like a big achievement} 8. h3 (8. d4 cxd4
9. cxd4 Bg4 10. d5 {transforms to the main line and is also very much
recommended}) 8... Be7 9. d4 Qc7 {no variation here is fun for Black. If he
does not take the pawns on d4, White will just push d4-d5 and cramp Black's
position, making the black knight feel awkward.} (9... cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11.
Nxd4 O-O (11... d5 {this forcing move doesn't solve Black's problems - He gets
a regular position, but pretty much by force loses a pawn or gets in an
inferior position} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bc4 Nb6 (13... Ndb4 $2 14. a3 Nxd4 15.
Qxd4 Nc2 16. Qxg7 Rf8 17. Bh6 Nxe1 18. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gd5f6,Gd5e7] And
White's attack is crushing}) (13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Nf6 15. Bg5 O-O 16. Nc3 h6
17. Rxe7 $1 hxg5 18. Rae1 Bc6 19. Qc5 Rc8 20. Qxg5 Bxg2 21. Bxf7+ Rxf7 22. Rxf7
Kxf7 23. Qxg2 $16) (13... Nf6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gb1c3,Ga1d1]})
14. Bg5 $1 O-O 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bxe7 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Rfe8 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. Bb4
$16) 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc1f4,Gd1d2,Ga1d1] because of the weakness on d6
White enjoys a lasting advantage. It can be easily targeted with Bf4, Qd2 and
Rad1}) 10. d5 Na5 11. b3 b5 12. Na3 O-O 13. c4 bxc4 14. bxc4 {[%cal Gc1d2,
Gd2c3] and the Black knight is completely shut out on a5 while White will base
all of his operations on the kingside. White will reposition his dark-squared
bishop on c3 where it will cover the important b2 and b4 squares, and move
everything else to the kingside.}) 8. h3 {If you want to keep it simple, you
can skip the chapters 2 and 3 and hope that this continuation will bring you
the desired results! However, I do believe that 8.d4 is much stronger and more
ambitious, and worth your attention!} (8. d4 $1 cxd4 9. cxd4 {will be covered
in Chapter 2 and Chapter 3, each analyzing the two best responses from Black -
9...e5 and 9...d5}) 8... Bxf3 (8... Bh5 $6 {this is extremely risky as Black
unexpectedly starts to experience some problems} 9. g4 Bg6 10. d4 $1 cxd4 11.
cxd4 d5 (11... Bxe4 $6 12. Rxe4 Nxe4 13. d5 $16 {[%cal Gd1a4]}) 12. exd5 Nxd5
13. Nc3 e6 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Bg2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd4d5] Black's lagging behind in
development and the looming Nf3-e5 threat spells trouble. For example,} Bb4 (
15... Rd8 16. Bg5 f6 17. Ne5 Qxd4 18. Nxc6 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 bxc6
21. Bxc6+ Kf7 22. Be3 $16) 16. Ne5 Qb5 (16... Qd6 17. Bf4 $1 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Qe7
19. Bxg7 Rg8 20. Bf6 Qxf6 21. Qa4+ Kf8 22. Qxb4+ $16) 17. a4 Qb6 18. a5 $1 Qb5
(18... Nxa5 19. Qa4+ Qb5 (19... Ke7 $4 20. d5 $1 Qb5 (20... Bxe1 21. Bg5+ f6
22. Qd7+ Kf8 23. dxe6 Qxf2+ 24. Kh1 fxe5 25. e7+ Kg8 26. Bd5+ Bf7 27. Qd8+ Rxd8
28. exd8=Q#) 21. Nxg6+ hxg6 22. Re4 $18) 20. Qxb5+ axb5 21. Nxg6 hxg6 22. Re5
$16) (18... Bxa5 $4 19. Bxc6+ bxc6 20. Nc4 $18) 19. Bd2 Bxd2 20. Qxd2 O-O 21.
Bxc6 bxc6 22. Rac1 $16) 9. Qxf3 e6 (9... g6 {perhaps is not so good as} 10. d3
Bg7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nd2 Nd7 13. Qd1 b5 14. Nf3 {and White will simply play Qd2
and d3-d4 by gaining some space advantage together with the Bishop pair} Nb6
15. d4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rc8 17. b3 Nb4 18. Rc1 Nxa2 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. Qa1 Nc3 21.
Qa5 Na8 22. Bd2 {1-0 (67) Zubarev,A (2588) -Kuzubov,Y (2661) Lvov 2014}) 10. d3
Be7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Qe2 $1 {This "anti-positional" move shows a good
understanding where White will position his pieces - the knight will jump to
f3 while the light-squared bishop will be activated by g2-g3 and Bg2} d5 13.
Nf3 b5 14. g3 Qb6 15. Bg2 dxe4 {This is accurate as now Black gets a clear
game plan. Otherwise, he risks being overwhelmed on the kingside where White
will base all of his future operations.} 16. dxe4 h6 17. Bf4 Rfd8 {There's not
much for White here except the Bishop pair. Black's play is quite
straightforward - either exchange both rooks on the d-file or play c5-c4,
Nf6-d7-c5. However, it is playable! If you're not happy with the results and
wish for more, let's head to the next two chapters!} 18. b3 *

