1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nc6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. d4
(8. h3 {this quiet alternative was covered in Chapter 1. It ensures White gets
the minimum advantage of two bishops.}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 e5 {A very ambitious
move by Black which can lead to some sharp variations} (9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 e5
11. d5 Nd4 12. Be3 {transforms to a variation which in a different order of
the moves will be covered shortly}) (9... g6 10. Be3 Bg7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. h3
Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nd7 14. Nb3 e5 15. Qd1 $14) 10. Be3 {Update! Given the recent
discoveries in the complex lines of 10.d5, I dediced the change the main move
of this chapter for a much simpler and less forced approach. Here Black has to
understand that the immediate taking on f3 with the bishop probably is a
positional inaccuracy.} (10. d5 {A more thorough analysis proves that Black
manages to get a good game if he can find several only and absolutely not
obvious moves so I will leave the decision up to you if you want to test Black.
} Nd4 11. Be3 Nxf3+ (11... Bxf3 $6 {transposes to a covered line earlier}) (
11... Be7 12. Bxd4 exd4 13. Nbd2 {transposes to a covered line earlier}) 12.
gxf3 Bd7 (12... Bh5 {feels really clumsy as the Bishop has nothing to do on h5
and it also slows down own counterplay with Nf6-h5} 13. Nd2 Be7 14. Bh3 {
[%cal Gd1b3,Ga2a4,Gd2c4] White is already much better and with a clear
gameplan - Qb3 and a2-a4, possibly also Nd2-c4} O-O 15. Qb3 b5 16. a4 Rb8 17.
Qc3 g5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra7 g4 20. fxg4 Nxg4 21. Bxg4 Bxg4 22. Bh6 Re8 23. Qg3
Kh8 24. h3 Bh4 25. Bg7+ Kxg7 26. Qxg4+ Qg5 27. Nf3 Qxg4+ 28. hxg4 Bd8 29. Rd7
Ba5 30. Ra1 {1-0 (49) Leniart,A (2455)-Piorun,K (2520) Warsaw 2012}) (12... Bc8
13. Nd2 Be7 14. Nc4 O-O 15. Nb6 Rb8 16. Rc1 Nd7 17. Nxc8 Rxc8 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19.
Bh3 {White keeps a pleasant edge and plans to use the c-file for a future
invasion}) 13. a4 {stopping the defensive resource b7-b5} Be7 14. Qb3 O-O {
This is not even a sacrifice but a necessity as Black can't really protect the
b7 pawn without serious consequences} (14... Rb8 15. Bb6 Qc8 16. Nd2 O-O 17.
Rec1 Qe8 18. Nc4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb3a3,Gb6c7] and Black's position falls
apart because of the eventual loss of the d6 pawn}) (14... Qb8 15. Na3 O-O 16.
Nc4 b5 (16... Bd8 17. Qb4 Bc7 18. Bb6 Ne8 19. Rec1 $16 {is hardly fun for Black
}) 17. Nb6 bxa4 18. Qc2 Ra7 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. Bxa6 $16) (14... Bc8 15. Na3 O-O
16. Nc4 Nh5 17. Rac1 f5 18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Nxc8 Rxc8 20. Bh3 Rxc1 (20... g6 21.
exf5 gxf5 (21... Qd7 22. f4 $1 exf4 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Bd4 gxf5 25. Qf3 Ng7 26.
Qxf4 Rf8 27. Qh6 Rf7 28. Kh1 $18) 22. Qxb7) 21. Rxc1 Bg5 22. Bxf5 Bxe3 23. fxe3
Qg5+ 24. Kh1 Qh4 25. Be6+ Kh8 26. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gc2g2,Gc2c8] and Black's
initiative has ended, leaving White up a healthy extra pawn}) 15. Na3 $5 {
Another way to try to trick your opponent by not hurrying to pick up the b7
pawn.} (15. Qxb7 {a deeper analysis with the help of the engines at a great
depth proves that Black equalizes the game after all.} Nh5 {of course, Black
has to seek an immediate counterattack on the kingside or this game will end
very quickly} (15... a5 16. Nd2 Rb8 17. Qa6 Nh5 18. Nc4 f5 19. Nxa5 Ra8 20. Nc6
$16) 16. Na3 $146 {worth a try but also here Black achieves a draw with the
perfect play.} (16. Nd2 Bg5 $1 {a fantastic only move which equals the game.} (
16... f5 {after this extremely logical move White should remain at the top} 17.
Nc4 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gb6d6,Gc4d6] with a positional threat of Nb6 or Qb6,
exchanging the queens and also attacking the d6 pawn} Rb8 (17... Nf6 18. Qb6
fxe4 (18... Qe8 19. Nxd6 Qg6+ 20. Kh1 $16) 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. Bb6 Rb8 21. fxe4
$16) (17... Bg5) 18. Qxa6 fxe4 (18... Qe8 19. Nb6 fxe4 20. Nxd7 Qxd7 21. Qc6 $1
Qf5 (21... Qd8 22. fxe4 {is good enough and Black doesn't have enough
compensation for the two sacrificed pawns} (22. a5 $5)) 22. Qc2 $14 {[%cal
Gf1g2,Ga4a8]}) 19. fxe4 Nf4 (19... Bc8 20. Qa7 Rb7 21. Qa5 Qe8 22. Bg2 Qg6 23.
Kh1 Bh4 24. Rf1 Rbf7 25. Qb6 Rf6 26. a5 {1-0 (37) Rambaldi,F (2560)-Williams,S
(2439) London 2015}) (19... Qe8 20. Bg2 Nf4 21. Bxf4 Rxf4 22. Ra3 {and Black's
compensation is questionable}) 20. Ra3 $1 {with this thematic move to transfer
the rook to g3 or to play f2-f3 White secures an edge. The game remains quite
sharp but with an accurate play White should remain on the top} Qe8 21. Bxf4
Rxf4 (21... exf4 {[%cal Rf4f3]} 22. f3 Ra8 (22... Bf6 23. Rd1 Ra8 24. Qb6 (24.
Qxd6 Be7) 24... Rb8 25. Qf2 Bxa4 26. Rc1 $16) 23. Qb6 Rxa4 24. Rxa4 Bxa4 25.
Qb7 $16) 22. f3 Ra8 23. Qb6 Rxa4 24. Rxa4 Bxa4 25. Bg2 {White has kept one
extra pawn and the king is safe. Perhaps with an accurate defense Black can
draw this but still it's only White is is going to enjoy the rest of the game.}
) 17. Qb4 $5 (17. Nc4 {[%cal Gc4b6]} Bxe3 18. fxe3 f5 $3 {of course, this is a
thematic move, but the consequences can be difficult to calculate if Black is
not perfectly prepared.} 19. exf5 (19. Nb6 fxe4 $3 20. Nxd7 (20. f4 $5 {
