1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ {I believe that this is the most
precise continuation if White wants to set up a Maroczy Bind with e4 and c4
pawns. It is possible to play 4.c4 first, but it involves a few more extra
lines to be studied, most notably taking on b5 or immediate Nc6.} Qxd7 {
[%cal Rb8c6,Rg8f6,Re7e6,Rf8e7,Re8g8,Rd6d5,Rd7g4] extremely logical - Black
intends to develop his knight on c6, the other on f6, then proceed with e7-e6,
Be7, 0-0 and probably d6-d5. Sometimes Qd7-g4 becomes a tangible threat.} (4...
Nxd7 {[%emt 0:00:06] the alternative continuation will be covered in Chapter})
5. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] the Maroczy Bind structure allows White to fight for
some space advantage and also slow down the thematic breakthroughs d6-d5 or
b7-b5. To be honest, this is one of the lines where Black should be equalizing
in the end. However, very often it's easier said than done - the position at
all times remains pleasant and comfortable to play for White, albeit very
often with nothing real. I will provide you with as many topical continuations
as I can so that you understand the essence of this setup, not necessarily all
exact lines.} (5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1 (7. d4 $5) 7... e6 8. d4 cxd4 9.
cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 {this is the old classical line
where Black is extremely solid.}) 5... Nf6 {it is probably smart for Black to
postpone the queenside knight development as sometimes (if White is inaccurate)
a swift action in the c-file will give him immediately an equal play.} (5...
Nc6 {Regarding White's plans, this doesn't change anything - we still want to
play Nc3, d2-d4, Nxd4, Be3 and f2-f3. It is Black who has to decide - whether
to put the bishop on g7 or e7} 6. Nc3 (6. d4 {This early move without
including Nc3 first appears to be playable, but it allows some funny
variations as an extra option for Black. You have to decide whether you need
it!} Qg4 $5 {[%cal Rg4g2,Rg4e4]} 7. d5 (7. O-O Nxd4 8. Nxd4 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 cxd4
10. Rxd4 g6 $11) 7... Qxe4+ 8. Be3 Nd4 9. Qa4+ b5 10. Qa6 Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Qd3+ $1
{[%cal Rc2b4]} 12. Kc1 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Rd8 14. Rd1 Qf5 15. Nh4 Qg4 16. Kxc2 Qe4+
17. Kc1 Qxc4+ 18. Nc3 Qxh4 19. Qb7 $13) 6... Nf6 (6... g6 7. d4 cxd4 (7... Bg7
8. Be3 {Doesn't really change anything}) 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 Nf6 10. f3 {
