11. O-O {[%cal Ga1c1,Gb2b3,Gd1d2,Gf1d1] While I will cover several possible
continuations here, I hope that by studying this chapter you will better
understand the main ideas and motifs of the Maroczy Bind, which is much more
important than remembering exact lines. I'll formulate some general rules I
discovered during my analysis: 1) Don't allow too many piece trades, most
importantly including the queens, unless you gain something for it. In some
occasions Black can go Nd7 with an idea to double take on d4 and play either
Qc5 or Qb6, forcing you to trade queens. 2) At the right moment, you can trade
the knights on c6 yourself, forcing Black to take with the pawn. When this
happens, think about typical ideas like c4-c5 or e4-e5, targeting the pawns.
If Black takes on c6 with a rook or queen, a2-a4 becomes a viable option to
stop the b7-b5 breakthrough for a long time, giving you a lot of time to
create your threats or at least some pressure. 3) I wouldn't suggest playing
a2-a4 if Black has two knights on the board - this will give him enough
counterplay by positioning one on on c6 and later maybe b4, and the other via
d7 to c5, targeting your weak b3 pawn. 4) If Black plays ...Rac8 without
exchanging the knights on d4, this is the best moment to retreat Nde2 to keep
more tension at the board as b7-b5 will come with less power 5) Be ready for
the b7-b5 at any given moment - most likely Black will play it sooner or later
otherwise he has no counterplay. When this happens, on most occasions you can
exchange the pawns and have a potential passed pawn for an endgame. Sometimes
there will be a tactical motif with c4-c5 possible, followed by e4-e5 and Nd5}
a6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Rb7b5] From here the order of the moves can vary a lot. Black
needs to understand where he is going to put his rooks first.} (11... e6 12.
Rc1 Rfd8 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Rf2 $6 {0-1 (33) Giri,A (2798)-Anand,V (2784)
Zuerich 2016} (14. Qe2 d5 (14... Qb7 15. Rfd1 d5 16. e5 Nd7 17. f4 Rab8 18. b3
{[%cal Gc3a4,Gc1c2,Gd1c1] with somewhat more pleasant position for White
although nothing much}) 15. e5 Ne8 16. Bc5 dxc4 17. f4 Qd3 18. Qf2 $14)) (11...
Rac8 12. b3 Rfd8 (12... a6 13. Qd3 {for Black this is a worse version of the
mainline as now after 13...Ne5 White doesn't have to keep an eye on the c4
pawn and can just play 14.Qd2, protecting the knight on c3 against b7-b5 and
thus with a stable plus.} e6 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. Rac1 Ne5 16. Qe2 {the main
problem for Black is to make d6-d5 to happen. If he goes for it while the
knight is on e5, White will almost always have f3-f4 and e4-e5 counterstrike,
securing a nice outpost for the knight on d4 and isolated pawn for Black on d5.
} Qe7 17. Rc2 Nc6 18. Rcd2 Ne8 (18... d5 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Bb6 Re8 21. Na4 $14)
19. Na4 (19. Nxc6 Rxc6 20. Na4 $14 {[%cal Ge3b6,Gc4c5]}) 19... Nxd4 20. Bxd4
Bxd4+ 21. Rxd4 Qg5 {1/2-1/2 (21) Zhigalko,S (2654)-Yilmaz,M (2582) Kocaeli 2015
}) (12... Qd8 {[%cal Rd8a5,Rf6d7] Black can try to rearrange his pieces by
putting the queen on a5 and the knight on d7.} 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. Nde2 $1 {
since the Black rook is already on c8, this is a good moment to retreat.} a6
15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Rac1 b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nd5 Qxd2 19. Rxd2 Nxd5 20. Rxd5 $14
) (12... b6 {[%cal Rd7b7,Ra7a6,Rb6b5] a slow way to make b6-b5 happen - White
will have plenty of time to prepare for it.} 13. Rc1 Qb7 14. Qd2 a6 15. Nxc6 $1
Rxc6 16. a4 $14) 13. Qd2 {the lines here are highly transpositional - there's
a huge variety of the order of the moves, how Black positions his pieces. As
soon as Black plays e7-e6, this is a good moment to trade the knights on c6 to
make the d6-d5 push less powerful, if possible at all.} e6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15.
Bg5 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf1d1] with the following moves Rac1 and Rfd1, shortly
eyeing to target the weak d6 pawn, or c4-c5 and e4-e5 at the right moment.
It's not clear if Black can even make d6-d5 happen without serious
consequences.}) (11... Rfc8 12. b3 a6 (12... Qd8 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. Rac1 a6 15.
Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Rfd1 b5 17. c5 $1 dxc5 18. e5 Ne8 19. Nd5 Qxd2 20. Rxd2 Re6 21.
Bxc5 $14) 13. Qd3 (13. Nxc6 $1) 13... Qd8 14. Rac1 (14. Nxc6 $5 Rxc6 15. Rac1
Qa5 16. Rfd1 Rac8 17. a4 $14) 14... Nd7 15. Rfd1 Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 b5
18. Nd5 bxc4 19. Rxc4 Rxc4 20. Qxc4 Nb6 21. Qc7 Nxd5 22. Qxd8+ Rxd8 23. Rxd5
Rc8 24. Ra5 Rc6 25. Kf2 Kf8 26. Ke3 Ke8 27. Kd3 {1/2-1/2 (40) Mamedov,R (2658)
-Vachier Lagrave,M (2765) Shamkir 2015}) 12. Qd3 $5 {this interesting idea was
first introduced in 2015 by IM Petter Haugli, and within months it was quickly
picked up by some very strong GMs as Rauf Mamedov, Sergei Zhigalko and Eltaj
Safarli, followed by others. White stops the immediate b7-b5 threat from Black
keeps an eye on the knight on d4, plans to develop the rooks on c1 and d1 and
at the same time provokes Black to play Ne5, after which the b5 breakthrough
becomes not as dangerous as it could be. This continuation to me looks more
appealing than the main move 12.a4 which has the same idea but is against my
principle not to play it if Black has two knights on the board as it would
give Black a good counterplay after the eventual e7-e6 and Nf6-d7-c5.} (12. a4
e6 {[%cal Rd6d5]} 13. Nde2 Qc7 14. Kh1 Nd7 15. b3 Rac8 16. Rb1 Nc5 17. Bg5 Rfe8
18. Qc2 Qa5 19. Bh4 {and a long maneuvering game begins}) (12. Qe2 $2 {this is
not an improvement of the idea as it is easily refuted by a classic tactic.}
Nxe4 $1 13. Nxc6 Nxc3) 12... Ne5 {this is not the only continuation, but it is
the most logical - Black uses the opportunity to go for a quick b7-b5
breakthrough without White even having an option to take the pawn. There are
other continuations with less forced play as well, but in none of them Black
reaches full equality.} (12... Rfc8 13. b3 Qd8 14. Rfd1 Nd7 {[%cal Rc6d4,Rg7d4,
Rd8b6]} 15. Nxc6 $1 Rxc6 16. Rac1 (16. Bd4 {1/2-1/2 (34) Zhigalko,S (2678)
-Topalov,V (2772) Tromsoe 2014}) 16... e6 17. Ne2 $14) (12... Rab8 13. b3 (13.
Nxc6 $5) 13... Nxd4 (13... Rfc8 {since Black now is postponing b7-b5 in hopes
for a better moment, White can switch the character of the position because
the black rook placement feels awkward.} 14. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 15. Rad1 $14 {
[%cal Ge4e5,Gc4c5]}) 14. Bxd4 b5 15. cxb5 axb5 16. a4 bxa4 17. bxa4 Rb4 18.
Rfb1 Rxb1+ 19. Rxb1 Ra8 20. Bb6 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5] and White has some
reasonable chances for a better endgame due to the passed a-pawn.}) (12... Qc7
13. b3 {this doesn't change much and leads to the typical structure.}) 13. Qe2
Rac8 14. b3 b5 (14... e6 15. Rac1 d5 $5 {later Black could not have such an
