1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. c4 e5 {[%cal Rg7g6,Rf8g7,Rb8c6,
Rg8e7,Re8g8] This relatively rare continuation has decent logic - Black closes
the center to avoid any "Maroczy Bind business" and plans to develop the
pieces by Nc6, g7-g6, Bg7, Nge7 and 0-0. Some other ideas have been tried here
as well, including the rare maneuver Be7-d8 with Nge7, or quick f7-f5-f4. It's
important to note that if Black plays perfectly there is no real advantage for
White, as in most of the Anti-Sicilian lines, just slightly more pleasant
positions for White to play.} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4] The best game plan
here for White after short castling is to prepare the b2-b4 push. By doing
this, you want to achieve one of the two things. 1) if Black doesn't play
b7-b6, take on c5 and force Black to take with the d pawn. Then after the
eventual Nc3-d5 maneuver Black will face an unpleasant choice - either ignore
the knight on d5 or take it. If the latter happens, White takes cxd5 and
continues to play with pawn minority at the queenside by some typical
maneuvers as Nf3-d2-c4, a3-a4-a5, and also f2-f4.2) If Black does play b7-b6,
intending to take on c5 with the b pawn, I suggest you play b4-b5 and transfer
the weight of the defense on the b6 pawn by the eventual a4-a5.} Nc6 7. O-O {
Probably it doesn't matter but perhaps castling before playing d2-d3 is more
accurate as it makes Black's unusual idea of Be7-d8 less likely to happen as
White will not have "wasted" tempo on d2-d3. There's a possibility that if
Black will grab the pawn on b4 after b2-b4, White can eventually go directly
d2-d4 in one move.} (7. d3 Be7 8. a3 Bd8 9. O-O Nge7 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 Nxb4
{In the following blitz game the fearsome World Champion Magnus Carlsen
accepted the challenge and picked up the b4 pawn because White had already
played d2-d3. Nevertheless, he got into trouble... but won the game anyway!}
12. Ba3 Nbc6 (12... Nec6 $5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. d4 exd4 16. Qxd4 $44)
13. d4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 O-O 16. e5 (16. Qxd6) 16... Nc6 17. Qxd6
Qxd6 18. exd6 Bf6 19. Rac1 Bxc3 20. Rxc3 Rfd8 21. Rb1 $16 {0-1 (38) Bacrot,E 
(2708)-Carlsen,M (2832) Paris 2017}) 7... g6 (7... Be7 {is an odd setup - the
bishop goes to d8, while the kingside knight is going to be developed on e7,
followed by a quick breakthrough f7-f5. Again, there's not much for White, and
he can base his entire game plan playing around that "bad" dark-squared bishop
on d8 or g7, wherever it will go.} 8. a3 Bd8 {Perhaps being inspired by his
greatest student (M.Carlsen) or maybe having analyzed the same variation
together, one month after the previously mentioned blitz game the World
Champion's coach and mentor Simen Agdestein decided to employ the same idea,
this time in a classical game.} 9. b4 Nge7 (9... cxb4 $6 {now obviously
grabbing the pawn looks less fun for Black because White managed to save one
tempo and play d2-d4 in one move.} 10. axb4 Nxb4 11. Ba3 Nc6 12. d4 $16) 10.
Rb1 O-O 11. d3 f5 12. bxc5 dxc5 13. Nd5 Ba5 14. Bb2 (14. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5e7]}
Ng6 15. h4 $1 h6 16. h5 $1 Nh8 17. Bc1 f4 18. Nh4 $16) 14... Ng6 15. Ng5 h6 16.
exf5 Qxf5 17. Ne4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (108) Tari,A (2593) -Agdestein,S (2604)
Stavanger 2017}) (7... Nge7 8. a3 f5 9. b4 f4 $6 {This doesn't look like a
serious continuation but rather a testing idea for one game from Black!} 10.
Nd5 b6 11. Ng5 $6 {the wrong direction} (11. g3 $1 Ng6 12. d3 Be7 13. b5 Nd8
14. gxf4 Nxf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. a4 $16) 11... Ng6 12. Qh5 Be7 13. Nxh7 $2 Kf7
14. Bb2 $2 Rxh7 $1 {0-1 (14) Cornette,M (2579)-Naiditsch,A (2663) Drancy 2016})
8. a3 Bg7 (8... a5 $6 {this idea, inspired by the English Opening, won't work
here.} 9. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5b6]} Ra6 10. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] and Black is unable to
stop b2-b4}) 9. b4 $1 {if White can make this push happen in one move without
playing Rb1, go for it! If Black plays b7-b6, White will play b4-b5,
transferring the weight to the b6 pawn, and the rook on a1 is situated
perfectly for further actions.} Nge7 {The best continuation - Black accepts
that bxc5 dxc5 is going to happen.} (9... cxb4 $2 {taking the pawn here is
dubious for Black as White quickly develops a strong attack.} 10. axb4 Nxb4 11.
Ba3 Nc6 12. Nb5 Bf8 13. d4 a6 14. dxe5 $1 (14. Nc3 $16) 14... axb5 15. Bb2 $18)
(9... b6 {this is also playable for Black but White's position always seems
more comfortable.} 10. b5 $1 {[%csl Rb6]} Nd4 11. a4 {For the time being White
will ignore the knight on d4 and would be very happy to exchange the remaining
bishop for the e7 knight. The problem with the direct approach of a4-a5 is
that Black can just take on a5, following with a quick a7-a6, probably
immediately equalizing. The potentially weak b6 pawn is going nowhere, and the
threat a4-a5 always will be in the air, so be patient.} (11. Nxd4 exd4 (11...
cxd4 $6 12. Nd5 Ne7 13. Nb4 $1 {[%cal Ga3a5]}) 12. Nd5 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 14. d3
O-O 15. a4 f5 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. a5 Raf8 18. f4 {possibly is also worth a try,
but perhaps it's too straightforward approach, and Black is holding without
many problems.}) 11... Ne7 12. d3 O-O 13. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5e7]} f6 14. Be3 a6 (
14... f5 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. a5 Rff8 18. Nd2 fxe4 19. dxe4 {[%csl
Rb6][%cal Ga1a8,Gd2f1,Gf1d5] and a long maneuvering game ensues, with slightly
better perspectives for White. He can increase the pressure on the a-file by
doubling some heavy pieces there before axb6. Another possible idea is to
reposition the knight from d2-f1-e3-d5 and increase the pressure on the b6
pawn. Either way, you can and probably should ignore the knight on d4.}) 15.
Nd2 axb5 16. axb5 Qb7 17. Bxd4 cxd4 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. cxd5 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rd6]
[%cal Gd2c4]}) 10. bxc5 {I think this is the only logical continuation given
the circumstances. If Black doesn't play b7-b6, there's not much sense to push
b4-b5, and it will be problematic to open any lines on the queenside later.
Other than that, there's nothing else to do for White.} dxc5 11. d3 {Now it
makes sense to base all of White's game plan on the "bad" bishop on g7,
combined with the bonus of the nice d5 outpost for your knight.} O-O 12. Nd5 {
This position can be tricky if both sides know the best continuations
beforehand. Probably Black has to push f7-f5 sooner or later to generate some
counterplay and aim for the fxe4 and Nd4 idea which is essentially the same
what White is aiming for with the d5 knight. There might be some other slow
continuations for Black like b7-b6, Rad8 but they change little in the fact
that without f7-f5 or exchanging the knight on d5 Black has nothing much to do.
} f5 (12... Nd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bf4 {feels more pleasant for White}) (12...
h6 $6 13. Bxh6 $1 {[%cal Gd5f6]} Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bxh6 15. dxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxe5 $14)
(12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nd4 (13... Ne7 14. Be3 b6 15. Nd2 Nc8 16. Nc4 Nd6 17. a4
$14) 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Qb3 Rfc8 16. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 13. Bg5 {If Black
does nothing significant, White will take on e7 with the bishop and leave the
knight on d5, and eventually improve the f3 knight.} fxe4 {forcing White's
hand.} (13... Nxd5 $5 14. exd5 Na5 (14... Nd4 15. Nxd4 cxd4 (15... exd4 16. Re1
$14) 16. Qb3 {[%cal Gf2f3]} e4 $5 {this allows some funny variations to happen
- otherwise White would just fix the position with f2-f3 and either increase
the pressure on the e5 pawn or play in the queenside.} 17. d6 $1 {[%cal Gb3g8]}
f4 {[%cal Rd7g4,Rf4f3]} 18. f3 $1 {as paradoxical as it is, the pawn on e3 is
not a big threat!} (18. dxe4 $2 Qg4 {[%cal Rg4g5,Rf4f3]}) 18... e3 19. c5+ Kh8
20. Rab1 b6 21. Be7 $16) 15. Bd2 e4 16. Rc1 exf3 17. Bxa5 fxg2 18. Kxg2 b6 19.
Bd2 Rae8 20. Qf3 {objectively with nothing for White but still it's him who
has the passed pawn on d5 and a better bishop. Perhaps it is possible to fight
for something more in the upcoming bishop endgame if it ever comes to it.}) (
13... Nc8 14. Be3 b6 15. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5]} f4 $6 16. Bd2 a5 17. Rb1 Nb4 18. g3
$1 Ra7 19. Bc3 Qd6 20. gxf4 exf4 21. Bxg7 Rxg7 22. Kh1 g5 23. Rg1 g4 24. Nh4
$14 {1-0 (42) Rublevsky,S (2685)-Brestian,E (2430) Elista 1998}) (13... h6 14.
Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Rb1 Nxd5 16. cxd5 $14 {[%csl Rg7]}) 14. Nxe7+ $1 {the most
accurate continuation to keep chances for a better endgame alive - White's
only hope is the bad bishop on g7.} Nxe7 15. dxe4 Qxd1 (15... Qc7 $6 16. Bxe7
Qxe7 17. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d5]}) (15... Rad8 $6 16. Qe2 Qe6 17. Bxe7 Qxe7
18. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gd1d5]}) 16. Rfxd1 Nc6 17. Rd5 {This is a nice square to
occupy!} b6 (17... Nd4 {perhaps this is more accurate as it forces the knight
retreat on d2 because of the Ne2-c3 threat. However, it still doesn't give
Black full equality.} 18. Nd2 b6 19. a4 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ga4a5] there's a lot of
room for improvements for White pieces. The same can't be said about the
bishop on g7.}) 18. Kf1 Nd4 19. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3,Ga3a4] The knight on d4
should be ignored and played around as it's doing nothing there anyway. I
don't think Black has equalized here.} h6 20. Be3 Rad8 21. a4 $1 {continuing
placing your pawns on the white squares and fixing opponent's pawns on the
color of his bishop. It is tough to suggest something good for Black and very
typical for such situations; his position can quickly deteriorate.} Rxd5 $6 {
perhaps not the best continuation but let's illustrate where it leads.} 22.
cxd5 Kf7 23. Rc1 h5 24. Nd3 Ke7 25. Nb2 Bf6 26. Nc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5]} *

