1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 {this move looks slightly
illogical as the knight usually is better developed on c6. Black has managed
to save one tempo for the development of the queen and can organize a quick
counterplay on the c-file, should it open. So what to choose for White? This
is why we make two normal developing moves 0-0 and Qe2 and see what happens
next.} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qe2 {a multi-purpose move. If Black plays g7-g6, White
can aim for the classical c2-c3 and d2-d4, claiming the center. If Black plays
e7-e6, then I suggest to go for the Maroczy Bind structure yet again and try
to break the ever solid Hedgehog structure.} e6 (6... g6 {this setup with the
queenside knight on d7 doesn't make much sense as Black isn't challenging the
center in any way} 7. c3 Bg7 8. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White firmly controls the
center and the possible threat e4-e5-e6 is always in the air} cxd4 (8... O-O 9.
e5 Nd5 10. e6 N7b6 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. exf7+ Rxf7 13. Ng5 Rf6 14. a4 $16) (8...
d5 $6 9. e5 Ne4 10. c4 e6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 O-O 14. Rb1 b6
15. Ng5 $14) 9. cxd4 d5 (9... O-O 10. Nc3 $14 (10. e5 $6 {in the current setup
this plan for White is less appealing than with the c3 and c5 pawns on the
board as the black knight can now jump to a more active square.} dxe5 11. dxe5
Nd5 12. e6 Nc5 $11)) 10. e5 Ne4 11. Qb5 e6 12. Qxb7 {and Black has to prove if
he actually has got any compensation for the lost pawn.}) (6... Rc8 $5 {
A very interesting move - before developing the remaining bishop Black wants
to see first which setup White will choose. White would want to play the
Maroczy Bind against the e7-e6 and Be7 setup so that Black will have the
eternal weakness on d6, and c2-c3 and d2-d4 against g7-g6 and Bg7 setup where
Black isn't really fighting for the center. Let us look at some alternative
lines which explain the dilemma White now faces.} 7. d3 {Taking into account
discoveries in the alternative variations, I have come to a conclusion that
this is the best choice for White. Treat it like Italian opening - neither
there's any advantage for White yet everyone loves it! After all, the black
knight on d7 feels misplaced and most likely will be rerouted to the more
active c6 square via b8. And Black did waste time for Rc8 which value can be
questioned in this closed position. We will try to follow two simple rules: 1)
against any Black's setup go for an eventual f2-f4 and organize an attack on
the kingside. 2) depending on where Black will develop his bishop, refrain
putting your own bishop on the same diagonal to avoid any unnecessary
exchanges, thus keeping the position more complex and uneasy to play for Black.
} (7. b3 {Black can now position the bishop on g7 with an inevitable bishop
exchange which is not great news for an ambitious White player.} g6 $1 8. Bb2
Bg7 9. d3 (9. d4 $6 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. Nd2 O-O 12. c4 {this doesn't look
like a good Maroczy Bind to me as the White knight should be on c3, not d2.}) (
9. c4 e5 $11 {not mandatory but logical - Black closes the center and the
whole White's setup with b3 and Bb2 looks like a waste of time.}) 9... O-O 10.
Nbd2 Nh5 11. Bxg7 Nxg7 $11) (7. Rd1 $5 {it would be interesting to respond
against a waiting move with a waiting move, but Black in return can play a few
more good waiting moves, including Qc7 and a7-a6 while White will simply run
out of them!} g6 $6 (7... e6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 a6 10. c4 Be7 11. b3 O-O 12.
Bb2 Qa5 13. Nc3 {this would lead to a Maroczy Bind and a similar position to
the main line, but the rook on d1 is misplaced for the f2-f4 and Nf3 plan}) (
7... Qc7 $5) (7... a6 $5) 8. c3 Bh6 $5 9. Na3 O-O 10. e5 $1 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5
12. d4 Bxc1 13. dxe5 Qb6 14. Raxc1 Nh5 15. Nc4 Qa6 16. g3 $14) (7. c3 {this is
a very logical continuation; however Black easily equalizes also here} e6 (7...
Qc7 {there have been some attempts to improvize more in this line but I don't
find this continuation as convicing for Black} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Qc4 (9... d5
$2 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 {[%csl Rc7]} Qc2 (11... Nxd2 12. Bxd2 e6 13. Rac1 Qb8
14. Rxc8+ Qxc8 15. Rc1 Qb8 16. Qb5 $16 {[%csl Rd7]}) 12. Ne1 Qc6 13. Nb3 Qg6
14. Qb5 Rc7 15. Qxd5 $18 {1/2-1/2 (71) Ghinda,M (2455)-Miles,A (2560) Dortmund
1979}) (9... Qxc1 $2 10. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 11. Ne1 g6 12. g3 $1 Bh6 13. Kg2 O-O 14.
Nd3 $16) 10. Qe3 g6 11. Bd2 Qa6 12. Nc3 Bg7 13. h3 O-O $6 14. e5 dxe5 15. dxe5
Ne8 16. Nd5 Qe6 17. Nf4 Qb6 18. e6 Ne5 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Nxe5 Qxe3 21. Bxe3
Bxe5 22. Nd3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (59) Bacallao Alonso,Y (2554)-Ortiz Suarez,I (2578)
Varadero 2016}) 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ng8 $1 (10... Ne4 $6 11. Be3 Nb6
12. Ne1 f5 13. f3 Ng5 14. b3 Nf7 15. Nd3 Nd7 16. Nd2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (30) Mamedov,
R (2680)-Ivanchuk,V (2729) Kocaeli 2017}) 11. Nc3 Ne7 12. Bg5 a6 13. Rad1 h6
14. Bc1 Nb6 $11 {1-0 (61) Khairullin,I (2651)-Zhigalko,A (2607) Minsk 2014})
7... g6 (7... e6 8. b3 {Since the Black bishop is going to e7, White avoids
putting his own bishop on the same diagonal.} Be7 (8... g6 $5 {Black could be
stubborn however playing cat and mouse sometimes can backfire!} 9. Na3 Bg7 10.
Bf4 $5 (10. Nc4) 10... Nh5 11. Bxd6 Bxa1 12. Rxa1 $13) 9. Bb2 O-O 10. h3 {
An important move to stop immediate Ng4 and Bf6, and preparing Nh2 and f2-f4.
Starting from here the game is not forced, and the following few variations
serve to illustrate what could potentially happen.} Nb8 (10... Ne8 11. Nbd2 Bf6
12. c3 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gd3d4]} d5 (12... g6 13. d4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rc2 $6 15.
Qd3 $1 Rxb2 16. Nc4 Rxf2 17. Rxf2 $14) 13. e5 Be7 14. c4 Nc7 15. Rac1 Nb8 16.
d4 b6 17. Rfd1 Nc6 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Ne4 d4 20. Ne1 Na6 21. Nd3) 11. Nbd2 Nc6
12. Nh2 Nd4 13. Qd1 Nd7 14. f4 Bf6 15. c3 Nc6 16. Ng4 b5 17. Nf3 {and White is
slowly building up the initiative on the kingside}) 8. Nc3 $146 Bg7 9. Bg5 {
To keep hopes alive for an initiative it's quite important to keep bishops on
the board. The bishop on g5 somewhat pins the knight on f6 guarding the e7
pawn and is provoking h7-h6 which might be a weakness to be targeted in the
middlegame.} O-O (9... h6 10. Be3 Ng4 (10... O-O 11. Nd2 Nb8 12. f4 Nc6 13.
Rae1) 11. Bd2 O-O (11... e6 12. h3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4 Nc6 15. Be3 Nd4
16. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gc3d1,Gc2c3]}) 12. h3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4 Nc6 15. f5
Nd4 16. Qg4) 10. Nd2 Nb8 11. f4 Nc6 12. Rae1 {with some attacking perspectives
on the kingside where White has concentrated most of his pieces. Black has no
weaknesses and objectively can't be worse, however, White has a clear gameplan
and can pressure Black into making an error.} b5 (12... Nd4 13. Qd1 b5 14. f5
b4 15. Ne2) 13. Nf3 b4 14. Nd5 e6 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Nd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 17.
Kh1 Re8 18. f5 $40) 15. Ne3) (6... e5 $6 7. c3 Be7 8. d4 O-O 9. dxe5 dxe5 (9...
Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. c4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5]}) 10. c4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rd7]
[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5]} Nb8 11. Rd1 (11. Nxe5 $5 Qd4 12. Bf4 Qxe4 13. Qxe4 Nxe4 14.
Re1 Ng5 15. Nc3 Ne6 16. Nd5 Bd6 17. Rad1 $14) 11... Qc7 12. Nc3 Nc6 13. Bg5 {
[%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5]} Nd4 14. Qd3 Rfd8 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 Qd6 17. Rab1 $14 {
[%csl Gd5,Rf6][%cal Gf3d4,Gb2b4,Gc4c5]}) (6... Qc7 $5 {this tricky move has
been played a number of times, most recently at Wijk Aan Zee 2018 B tournament
between Vidit Santosh Gujrathi and Anton Korobov. With the exact idea as 6...
Rc8, Black postpones the decision where to develop his bishop. I suggest you
treat it the same way as 6...Rc8 - go for a closed structure so that the Qc7
maneuver will feel like a waste of time. Again, the principle remains the same
- avoid trading the bishops by refraining from developing it on the same
diagonal, and plan an assault at the kingside.} 7. d3 {the main difference
between 6...Qc7 and 6...Rc8 is that now occasionally White can win some tempos
with Nc3-d5 or force useful exchanges.} (7. Rd1 e6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Rc8 10.
Nb5 Qxc2 11. Qxc2 Rxc2 12. N1a3 Rc8 13. Nxa7 Rd8 14. N7b5 Nxe4 15. f3 Nef6 16.
Nxd6+ Bxd6 17. Rxd6 Ke7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (31) Vidit,S (2718)-Korobov,A (2652) Wijk
aan Zee 2018}) 7... e6 (7... g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Bg5 O-O (9... h6 10. Be3 Ng4 11.
Bd2 O-O 12. h3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4 Nc6 15. f5 $40) 10. Nd2 e6 11. f4) 8.
Nbd2 $146 Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Nh5 11. g3 Bf6 12. c3 $1 g6 13. d4) 7. d4 {
the order of the moves by setting up the Maroczy Bind probably matters - if
White will choose c2-c4 before d2-d4, it gives Black a very interesting
defensive resource Nd7-e5!} (7. c3 {against e7-e6 setup this plan for White
doesn't impress me, mostly because Black's play is too straightforward and
easy to find. Of course, still, it remains playable} Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5
$1 10. e5 Ne4 11. Ne1 Qb6 12. Be3 f6 13. f3 Ng5 14. Nd3 O-O 15. Nd2 Qa6 16.
Rfe1 Rac8 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Nb3 {1/2-1/2 (59) Mastrovasilis,D (2606)-Jakubiec,
A (2515) Poland 2016}) 7... cxd4 {quite forced otherwise e4-e5 threat is
already in the air} 8. Nxd4 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Black can't really
stop White from setting up the Maroczy Bind.} Be7 (8... Qa5 $5 9. c4 Qe5 {
[%cal Re5d4,Re5e4]} 10. Be3 $1 a6 (10... Nxe4 $2 11. Nb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5a7,
Gb5c7]}) (10... Qxe4 $2 11. Nc3 Qe5 12. Ndb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5a7,Gb5c7]}) 11. Nd2
Qh5 (11... Nxe4 $4 12. f4 {[%csl Re4]}) 12. f3 Be7 13. b4 {[%csl Rh5]} O-O 14.
Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gd2f1]}) (8... d5 $6 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 11.
Qxe6+ Ne7 12. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1g5]}) (8... Nc5 9. f3 Be7 10. c4 O-O 11.
Nc3 {and most likely the game will transform to the main line - the knight on
c5 does nothing really}) (8... a6 9. c4 g6 $5 {an interesting way for Black to
meet the Maroczy Bind! However, since Black already committed himself to
playing e7-e6, the weakness on d6 remains.} (9... Rc8 10. b3 g6 11. Rd1 Bg7 {
this would be another clever order of the moves to put the bishop on g7
against the Maroczy Bind. This time the only change in White's plan is the
approach of the weakness on d6 - the bishop goes not to f4, but a3} 12. Ba3 Qb6
(12... Qc7 $6 13. Nc3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gd4e6,Ga3d6]} O-O 14. e5 $1 Nxe5 $2 15. Nxe6
$1 fxe6 16. Bxd6 $16) 13. Nc3 Nc5 (13... O-O 14. Na4 Qc7 15. Nf3 $14 {[%csl
Rd6]}) 14. Rab1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc3a4,Ge4e5] and now some tactical motifs
appear because of the x-ray possibilities of the bishop on a3. I will provide
you with some of the lines that illustrate the ideas.} O-O (14... Qa5 15. Na4
