1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ra7a6] Finally we will learn
what are we going to play against one of the most popular and aggressive
responses from Black. In this Anti Najdorf line which has often been used by
all of the Najdorf experts, including Garry Kasparov, Veselin Topalov, Maxime
Vachier - Lagrave, Hikaru Nakamura, and others. Although voluntarily closing
his light-squared bishop on c8, it is a standard, yet very ambitious defense.
Black doesn't want to trade the bishops to keep the game more complex and
possibly aim for a two bishop advantage for some possible long-term benefits.
While we will pursue the currently most modern continuation, I'll add two more
sidelines, which I was considering as serious alternatives, for some
occasional use or just for general knowledge.} 4. O-O (4. a4 $5 {an exciting
move with two possible ideas - either go for a quick a4-a5-a6 march and enjoy
slightly more pleasant position due to the open a-file and the weakness on a6,
or just push d2-d4 and Qxd4, either with the pawn on a4 or a5. Both ideas need
to be examined much more before giving a final verdict.} Ngf6 5. Nc3 e6 (5...
g6 6. a5 Bg7 7. a6 {not mandatory} O-O 8. O-O e6 9. d3 Qb6 10. axb7 Bxb7 11.
Re1 Rfd8 12. Ba4 h6 13. h3 d5 14. e5 Nh7 15. Bxd7 $1 Rxd7 16. d4 cxd4 17. Ne2
$14 {1-0 (30) Carlsen,M (2822) -Dreev,A (2648) Tbilisi 2017}) 6. a5 $5 (6. d4
cxd4 7. Qxd4 a6 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 {this probably is a quite harmless
Hedgehog setup, but it remains very much playable for White.} 10. Rd1 Qc7 11.
Bg5 Be7 12. Nd2 h6 13. Bh4 Ne5 14. Nf1 Rd8 15. Bg3 O-O 16. Ne3 $13 {1-0 (50)
Nakamura,H (2776)-Topalov,V (2800) Caleta 2015}) 6... a6 7. Be2 $146 {I find
it quite unbelievable that this already would be a novelty!} Be7 (7... d5 $5 8.
exd5 exd5 9. d4 c4 10. O-O Bb4 11. Bg5 {and so on}) 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 {
and now Black can't put the Hedgehog anymore. I won't be surprised that we
will see some more action in this line real soon.}) (4. d4 {the old approach
which right is considered as relatively harmless for Black, although he needs
to be accurate.} cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. Nc3 {and here, if Black
eventually will go e7-e5 and h7-h6, I suggest employing the idea of Nf3-d2-c4
or f1-e3. The setup always remains the same.} e5 8. Qd3 h6 9. Nd2 Rc8 10. Nc4
Be6 11. Ne3 Nf6 12. O-O Be7 13. a4 O-O 14. Rd1 {the order of the moves can
change, but the position quite inevitably goes to this moment.} Qc7 (14... Rc5
15. Bd2 (15. b3 $5) 15... Qc8 16. Be1 Rd8 17. b4 $6 (17. Ncd5 $5 Nxd5 18. exd5
Bg4 19. f3 Bh5 20. Bb4 e4 21. Qxe4 Bg5 22. Ra3 Bg6 23. Qd4 Bxe3+ 24. Rxe3 Rxc2
$11) 17... Rc7 18. a5 Bc4 19. Qd2 d5 20. Ncxd5 Nxd5 21. exd5 Bg5 $15 {1/2-1/2 
(31) Anand,V (2783)-Kasparov,G (2812) Saint Louis 2017}) 15. Bd2 Bc4 16. Nxc4
