1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Re1 e6 {one of the
most popular responses from Black. Now according to this whole setup White has
to play c2-c3 and only then Black will play b7-b5, avoiding any c2-c4 business
which will be covered in the last chapter of this database. This is the latest
modern theory of anti-Najdorf thus a lot of lines are still unexplored and
unknown to the general public. There are very few games to take examples from,
and most of them were played in 2017. So I won't claim that I've analyzed all
of the possible lines and that I understand the deepest nuances of every
single position so if you spot a mistake in my analysis, I truly apologize! I
did my best to offer you the best possible insight into these modern lines,
and I hope you'll make good use of them!} 7. c3 b5 8. Bc2 {now obviously c3-c4
would be just a waste of time.} c4 {the main move - Black stops White from
advancing d2-d4. The alternative move 8...Bb7 gives White a far more simple
and pleasant game.} (8... Bb7 9. d4 Be7 {If Black doesn't want to trade the
c-pawns, this is probably the most reasonable continuation.} (9... Qc7 $5 {
[%cal Rc7e5] a logical idea, Black stops White from advancing the e-pawn, but
it has a drawback - now another pawn advances!} 10. d5 exd5 (10... e5 11. a4
Be7 12. Na3 $14) 11. exd5+ Be7 12. a4 $1 $146 {and because of the weak b-pawn
and the pin on the e-file White gets a better position} (12. Bg5 $6 {0-1 (24)
