1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Re1 b5 7. c4 (7. c3 {
by playing this you can hope to transform to some of the lines that were
covered in Chapter 8 and simply skip this one. However this would give more
possibilities for Black as he's not really obliged to play e7-e6 and could opt
for e7-e5 for instance. Plus the main line in this chapter looks really good
for White and if the best players in the world are playing it, there must be a
reason!} Bb7 8. Bc2) 7... bxc4 {I am treating this as the main line because
it's more solid than the extravagant 7...g5!? which leads to a very dynamic
play but objectively Black doesn't equalize there.} (7... g5 $5 {It was first
introduced in 2015 when at Sinquefield Cup Veselin Topalov surprised Magnus
Carlsen, and won the game. Since then the continuation has been tested
numerous times and White has been scoring really well so far.} 8. Nxg5 (8. cxb5
$5 {if you want some fireworks, this continuation is for you - the
complications are immense.} g4 9. e5 (9. Nh4 e6 {[%csl Rh4]}) 9... dxe5 10. Ng5
Bg7 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Nc3 Nb6 13. bxa6 c4 14. Bc2 $13 {1/2-1/2 (44) Bartel,M 
(2622)-Grischuk,A (2774) Berlin 2015}) 8... Ne5 {the whole point of the idea -
Black wins back the pawn on c4 and has some counterplay at the g-file. However,
in long term the Black king has no good shelter.} 9. Be2 bxc4 10. Nc3 {[%cal
Gd2d4] now White plans to play d2-d4} (10. Na3 $6 Rg8 11. Nxc4 $6 Nxc4 12. d4
Nb6 13. Bh5 Nxh5 14. Qxh5 Rg7 $6 (14... Rxg5 $1 15. Bxg5 cxd4 16. Qxh7 Nd7 $17)
15. Nxh7 Qd7 16. dxc5 dxc5 17. e5 $2 (17. Nxf8 Qh3 18. Qxh3 Bxh3 19. g3 Nc4 20.
Bh6 Rg8 21. Rec1 {'='} Rh8 22. Bg7 Rg8 23. Bh6 $11) 17... Qc6 18. f3 Qg6 19.
Nf6+ Kd8 20. Qxg6 Rxg6 $17 {0-1 (40) Carlsen,M (2853)-Topalov,V (2816) Saint
Louis 2015}) 10... Rg8 (10... Rb8 11. Rf1 (11. f4 $5 Nd3 12. Bxd3 cxd3 13. Qa4+
Qd7 14. Qc4 h6 15. Qxf7+ Kd8 16. Nh3 Qg4 17. Nf2 Qxf4 18. e5 dxe5 19. Re3 $14)
(11. d4 cxd3 12. Bxd3 {probably is also very much playable}) 11... h6 12. Nf3
Nd3 13. Ne1 $1 Nxb2 (13... Rg8 $5 14. Kh1 Qd7 15. f3 (15. Nxd3 $2 cxd3 16. Bxd3
Rxg2 17. Kxg2 Qh3+ 18. Kh1 Ng4) 15... Nh5 16. Bxd3 cxd3 17. Nxd3 Bg7 18. Nf2
$14) 14. Bxb2 Rxb2 15. Bxc4 Rb4 16. Qe2 Bg7 17. Nc2 Rb6 18. Rab1 $14 {1-0 (38)
Carlsen,M (2834)-Grischuk,A (2747) London 2015}) (10... Bh6 $6 11. Nf3 Nd3 12.
Bxd3 cxd3 13. e5 $1 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Kf8 15. Qf3 Be6 16. Nxd3 $16 {1-0 (72) Ter
Sahakyan,S (2601)-Ponomariov,R (2715) Gjakova 2016}) 11. d4 cxd3 (11... cxd4 $5
$146 12. Qxd4 Bg7 13. Bxc4 {now the game is very much forced and leads to a
slightly better endgame for White.} (13. Qd1 $5) 13... h6 14. Nxf7 Nxf7 $1 15.
e5 $1 dxe5 (15... Nxe5 $4 16. Bxg8 Nxg8 17. Qd5 $18 {[%cal Gd5g8,Gd5a8]}) (
15... Ng4 16. Qd5 $18 {[%cal Gd5f7,Gd5a8]}) 16. Qxd8+ Nxd8 17. Nd5 $1 Kf8 18.
Nb6 Rb8 19. Nxc8 Rxc8 20. Bxg8 Nxg8 (20... Kxg8 21. Rxe5 Kf7 22. Ra5 $14) 21.
Be3 Nf6 22. Rac1 Rb8 23. b3 $14) 12. Bxd3 {All of this has been played before.
Now Black has several options - if he doesn't take the bishop, White will
retreat with it to e2 as it safeguards many important squares around the king.}
Rb8 (12... Bg7 13. Be2 h6 14. Nf3 Nfd7 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bf4 Rb8 17. Qd2 $14 {
Black hasn't equalized, and the king will always be in danger.}) (12... h6 13.
Nf3 Bg4 (13... Bh3 14. Bf1 Nfd7 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bf4 $16) 14. Be2 Bxf3 15.
Bxf3 Qd7 16. Bf4 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Qg4 18. Qxg4 Rxg4 19. g3 Nh5 20. Be3 Bg7 21. f3
Rg6 22. Rac1 $14) (12... Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Bb7 14. Nf3 Qd7 15. Bf4 Nh5 16. Bg3 Nxg3
17. hxg3 $14 {White's position is slightly more preferable due to the easy
game plan - play in the center. Black has to be extremely accurate not to land
into trouble very quickly.}) (12... Nfg4 13. Be2 h6 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Rb8
16. Nd5 Ne5 17. Bh5 e6 18. Nf4 Nc6 19. g3 {with a slightly more comfortable
position for White.}) 13. Be2 h6 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Nd7 {[%cal Rg8g2,Rb8b2,
Rd7e5,Re5c6,Rc6d4] perhaps this is the best setup for Black - he controls two
semi-open files with his both rooks, and the knight can maneuver in the center
with Nd7-e5-c6-d4. However, the fact doesn't change that his king will stay
forever in the center. Thus it's only logical for White not to trade queens
unless gaining something real out of it and slowly prepare to open the
position.} 16. Rb1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gf3h5]} Bg7 17. Nd5 e6 18. Ne3 Bd4 19. Nc4 (19.
Nc2 $5) 19... Ne5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. g3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] with a comfortable
edge for White. Black has two weak pawns on h6 and a6, and the king is not
feeling secure. In the meantime White has no weaknesses, he has managed to
stop any counterplay at the g-file and wants to open some files to get to the
king. Probably the best attempt to do this would be a well-timed b2-b4.}) (7...
Ne5 {although a very typical maneuver for this structure, here its value is
questionable as Black will have to deal with the consequences of the weak b5
pawn.} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. Be2 $1 {This is much stronger than 9.Bf1 - Black is
struggling as White very quickly opens the queenside in his favor. Black still
needs to bring his king to safety.} b4 (9... Bd7 10. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3g3,Gb1c3,
Gc3d5]} Rb8 (10... Qb8 11. Nc3 b4 12. Nd5 $14 {[%cal Ga2a3]}) 11. Qg3) 10. a3
e6 11. d3 Be7 12. axb4 cxb4 13. Be3 O-O 14. Nd2 Bd7 15. Nb3 (15. c5 {0-1 (27)
Sunilduth Lyna,N (2398)-Adhiban,B (2624) Pune 2014}) 15... a5 16. d4 $14 {
and White's advantage is obvious}) (7... Rb8 {a natural choice - Black defends
the weak b5 pawn. However, it gives White a very easy and comfortable position.
} 8. Nc3 $5 (8. cxb5 axb5 9. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb1c3] with a very clear game
plan for White - b2-b4 to fix the weak b5 pawn, followed by Nc3. This position
doesn't look fun for Black.} Ne5 (9... e6 10. b4 Be7 11. Nc3 c4 12. Bf1 Ba6 13.
d3 O-O 14. Bd2 $14 (14. Nd4 {1-0 (52) Heimann,A (2576)-Akshat, K (2381) Basel
2018})) (9... e5 10. b4 Be7 11. Nc3 Ba6 12. bxc5 (12. Bf1 {0-1 (45) Borisek,J 
(2561)-Salinas Herrera,P (2466) Doha 2016}) 12... Nxc5 13. Bc2 O-O 14. d4 $14)
(9... b4 10. Bc4 e6 11. axb4 Rxb4 12. d3 Be7 13. Bd2 Rb8 14. Ba5 Nb6 15. Nc3
Bd7 16. d4 cxd4 17. Qxd4 $14) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qe2 Ba6 12. b4 e6 13. Nc3 Nd7
14. Nxb5 Be7 15. Bb2 (15. Bc4 {1/2-1/2 (34) Svidler,P (2759) -Vachier Lagrave,
M (2798) Biel 2016}) 15... O-O 16. Reb1 $14) 8... b4 9. Nd5 e5 10. a3 a5 11.
Bc2 $14 {also feels great for White}) (7... b4 {this move can't be good - here
Vidit Santosh Gujrathi recently won a truly model game.} 8. a3 bxa3 9. Rxa3 e5
10. Nc3 Be7 11. Bc2 O-O 12. d3 Nb8 13. Ba4 Bd7 14. Bg5 Ra7 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16.
Nd5 Be6 17. Qb3 Bxd5 18. cxd5 Qc7 19. Nd2 Rb7 20. Qc3 Rb4 21. Nc4 Be7 22. Rea1
g6 23. Rb3 Rxb3 24. Bxb3 Bd8 25. Ba4 f5 26. Ra3 fxe4 27. dxe4 Qf7 28. Qc2 Bh4
29. g3 Be7 30. Rb3 Qf6 31. Rb7 {1-0 (39) Vidit,S (2718)-Harika,D (2497) Wijk
aan Zee 2018}) 8. Bxc4 Nb6 9. d3 $1 {There's an interesting nuance in this
position - if Black tries to close the center with e7-e5, then White doesn't
want to retreat with the bishop on b3 and force Black to take on c4 to build
his whole game plan around the d5 square. If Black plays e7-e6, then White
will retreat with the bishop to b3 and go for d3-d4.} (9. Bb3 e5 10. d3 Be7 11.
h3 O-O 12. Nc3 Ne8) 9... e6 (9... e5 10. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5]} Nxc4 {Black has to
take on c4 sooner or later.} (10... Be7 11. Ba5 Rb8 12. b4 cxb4 13. Bb3 O-O 14.
Nbd2 $14) 11. dxc4 h6 {a logical choice - Black doesn't want to allow the
typical Bg5xf6 maneuver and keep his knight for some hopes to eventually to
transfer it to d4.} (11... Be7 12. Bg5 O-O (12... Ng8 13. Be3 Nf6 14. Nc3 O-O
15. Bg5 {transforms}) 13. Nc3 h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qd3 Be6 16. Rad1 Be7 17. Nd2
$14 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5,Ge3f5] White's plan is fairly simple - Use the
knights for the d5 and f5 squares. If Black tries to do anything at the
queenside with a6-a5-a4, after the first attempt you can block it with a2-a4
and position one of your knights at the b5 square.}) 12. Nc3 Be7 13. h3 O-O 14.
Nh2 Be6 15. b3 Nd7 16. Ng4 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gg4e3,Ge3f5] White wants to put
one knight on d5, another on f5 and aim for either b3-b4 or f2-f4. Black
remains very solid.}) 10. Bb3 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O (11... e5 {with a loss of tempo
this looks strange, but still it remains playable. It's not clear if Black
should stop the d3-d4 push at all costs.} 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nc4 $14) 12. d4 cxd4
(12... d5 $5 $146 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. e5 {and again we have a French defense
structure! The Black knight on b6 feels slightly misplaced for it.} Nfd7 (14...
Ng4 15. Re2 f6 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. h3 Nxf2 18. Rxf2 $16 {this doesn't look
dangerous for White as Black's pieces are too far to start an offensive.}) 15.
Bc2 f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 (16... Qxf6 $6 17. Qd3 g6 18. Bg5 Qg7 {[%csl Re6][%cal
Rc5f2,Rd7c5]} 19. Bb3 $16) 17. Bf4 Nc4 18. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gc2d3,Ga1d1,Gf4g3,
Gf3e5,Gf3g5] it is much easier to play with White - there are a lot of good
position improving moves.}) (12... c4 $6 {releasing the tension in the center
only makes it easier for White} 13. Bc2 Bb7 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bf4) 13. Nxd4 {
this position has some resemblance with the Fischer - Sozin attack. The bishop
on b3 is situated perfectly for a potential f2-f4-f5 push or some thematic
sacrifices on e6.} Bd7 {by no means the following moves from now on are forced,
but they at least illustrate where the game potentially could be heading.} (
13... Bb7 $6 14. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Nxe6 Qc8 16. Nxf8 Kxf8 17. Bf4 Qe6 18. Qd4
Nbd7 19. Rad1 Ne5 20. Qb6 {1-0 (62) Kollars,D (2505)-Baert, A (2164) Caleta
2018}) 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 a5 {[%cal Ra5a4]} 16. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5]} Rc8 17. Qd3
Qc7 18. f3 {[%cal Gh4f2]} (18. f4 $5 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) 18... Nc4 19. Ndb5 Bxb5
20. Nxb5 Qc5+ 21. Bf2 Qb4 22. Bxc4 Rxc4 23. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5] because of
the slightly weak Black pawn on a5 and the nice outpost for the knight on b5,
White enjoys a stable plus.} *

